{"title_page": "Russia women's national water polo team", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox national water polo team\n| Gender             = women\n| Name               = Russia\n| FINA code          = RUS\n| Nickname           = \n| Image              = Flag of Russia.svg\n| Image_size         = \n| Association        = All Russian Swimming Federation\n| Confederation      = LEN\n| Coach              = [[Alexandr Gaidukov (water polo)|Alexander Gaidukov]]\n| Asst coach         = [[Andrey Belofastov]]\n| Captain            = [[Ekaterina Prokofyeva]]\n| Most caps          = \n| Top scorer         = \n| Home venue         = \n| FINA ranking       = 2\n| FINA ranking date  = February 2020\n| FINA highest       = 2\n| FINA highest year  = 2017, 2018, 2019\n| FINA lowest        = 7\n| FINA lowest year   = 2008\n| First game         = \n| Biggest win        = \n| Biggest defeat     = \n| Olympics apps      = 5\n| Olympics first     = 2000\n| Olympics best      = {{bronze3}} ([[Water polo at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000]], [[Water polo at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016]])\n| World champ apps   = 12\n| World champ first  = 1994\n| World champ best   = {{bronze3}} ([[2003 FINA Women's World Water Polo Championship|2003]], [[2007 FINA Women's World Water Polo Championship|2007]], [[Water polo at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's tournament|2009]], [[Water polo at the 2011 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's tournament|2011]], [[Water polo at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's tournament|2017]])\n| World cup apps     = 7\n| World cup first    = 1995\n| World cup best     = {{silver2}} ([[1997 FINA Women's Water Polo World Cup|1997]])\n| World league apps  = 15\n| World league first = 2004\n| World league best  = {{gold1}} ([[2008 FINA Women's Water Polo World League|2008]])\n| Regional name      = [[European Water Polo Championship|European Championship]]\n| Regional cup apps  = 14\n| Regional cup first = [[1993 Women's European Water Polo Championship|1993]]\n| Regional cup best  = {{gold1}} ([[2006 Women's European Water Polo Championship|2006]], [[2008 Women's European Water Polo Championship|2008]], [[2010 Women's European Water Polo Championship|2010]])\n| Website            = {{URL | https://www.waterpolo.ru | waterpolo.ru }}\n}}\n{{MedalTableTop}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{RUS}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Water polo at the Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[Water polo at the 2013 Summer Universiade|2013 Kazan]]|}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[Water polo at the 2009 Summer Universiade|2009 Belgrade]]|}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[Water polo at the 2011 Summer Universiade|2011 Shenzhen]]|}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[Water polo at the 2015 Summer Universiade|2015 Gwangju]]|}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[Water polo at the 2019 Summer Universiade|2019 Naples]]|}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[European Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2015 European Games|2015 Baku]]|[[Water polo at the 2015 European Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\nThe '''Russia women's national water polo team''' represents [[Russia]] in international [[women]]'s [[water polo]] competitions and friendly matches. The team is one of the leading teams in [[Europe]] since the mid-1990s.\n\n==History==\n===In the Russian Empire===\nWater polo in Russia dates back to 1910, when the sport was included into the national water sports programme. The Shuvalov school was opened back then, featuring rules that differed from the international rules. In 1913, the first water polo tournament was played between the Shuvalov school and [[Moscow]], with the first winning 3\u20132. The new sport progressed in Russia, as all swimming organizations included this sport into their programme. P. Erofeev and A. Shemansky further populized water polo by publishing brochures with rules and hints.<ref>[http://www.waterpolo.ru/xml/t/History.xml?lang=ru&cmd=view&nic=history&mid=152&rid=0&m1id=25&pid=8#8 \u0420\u0410\u0417\u0412\u0418\u0422\u0418\u0415 \u0412\u041e\u0414\u041d\u041e\u0413\u041e \u041f\u041e\u041b\u041e \u0412 \u0420\u041e\u0421\u0421\u0418\u0419\u0421\u041a\u041e\u0419 \u0418\u041c\u041f\u0415\u0420\u0418\u0418]</ref>\n\n===In the Soviet Union===\nAs previously, water polo was predominant in Moscow and [[Leningrad]] (formerly known as St. Petersburg). However, this changed when the water polo teams of the [[Black Sea Fleet]], [[Baltic Fleet]] and [[Caspian Flotilla]] further spread water polo in Russia. In the early history, water polo was popular especially among [[sailor]]s. The strongest teams were Delfin of Leningrad and the Moscow Life Saving Society and the Yacht-Club. Following the resolution by the organizing bureau of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] in 1925, [[physical culture]] has been greatly propagated in Russia, stimulating water polo as well.<ref name=\"Soviet\">[http://www.waterpolo.ru/xml/t/History.xml?lang=ru&cmd=view&nic=history&mid=152&rid=0&m1id=25&pid=9#9 \u0420\u0410\u0417\u0412\u0418\u0422\u0418\u0415 \u0412\u041e\u0414\u041d\u041e\u0413\u041e \u041f\u041e\u041b\u041e \u0412 \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420]</ref>\n\nThe first championship took place in 1925. Apart from the teams of Leningrad, Moscow and [[Kiev]], the tournament featured teams from the [[Caucasus]], [[Crimea]], [[Ural (region)|Ural]], as well as the aforementioned fleet teams. Three years later, water polo was included in the All-Union Spartakiade (sports festival). The team of Leningrad dominated in Russian water polo until 1933, as the city had winter water pools and so had more training opportunities. In 1946, the USSR Water Polo Cup was introduced. One year later, the Soviet Union was selected into the [[FINA]]. The national water polo then debuted at the [[1952 Winter Olympics]] in Helsinki.<ref name=\"Soviet\"/>\n\n==Results==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n===Olympic Games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!Year<ref name=\"HistoFINA PDF\">{{cite web|title=HistoFIN