]], [[Elena Smurova]], [[Olga Turova]] and [[Evgeniya Protsenko]]. Head Coach: [[Alexander Kleymenov]].\n\n* [[Water polo at the 2015 European Games \u2013 Women's tournament|2015 European Games]] \u2013 {{gold1}} ''Gold medal''\n:*[[Maria Bersneva]], [[Anastasia Fedotova]], [[Daria Gerzanich]], [[Evgenia Golovina]], [[Anna Isakova]], [[Polina Kempf]], [[Bella Khamzaeva]] ''(c)'', [[Elena Kotanchyan]], [[Alena Serzhantova]], [[Svetlana Stepakhina]], [[Veronika Vakhitova]], [[Elizaveta Zaplatina]], [[Aleksandra Zelenkovskaya]]. Coaches: [[Andrei Belofastov]], [[Alexander Fedoseev]].\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.sportkinef.com/ SportKinef]\n*[https://vk.com/eurogamesbaku2015 Gold Russian Waterpolo Girls. Baku 2015]\n\n{{National sports teams of Russia}}\n{{LEN Water polo women's national teams}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Women's water polo tournament winners\n|bg = gold\n|list1 = \n{{FINA Women's Water Polo World League winners}}\n{{Women's European Water Polo Championship winners}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Women's national sports teams of Russia|Water polo]]\n[[Category:Women's national water polo teams]]\n[[Category:Women's water polo in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russia national water polo team| ]]\n", "name_user": "Phikia", "label": "safe", "comment": "{{Infobox national water polo team}} parameters", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russia_women%27s_national_water_polo_team"}
{"title_page": "Wisconsin Highway 49", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Highway in Wisconsin}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=WI\n|type=WI\n|route=49\n|length_mi=127.52\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"WH1\">{{cite web |last = Bessert |first = Chris |title = Wisconsin Highways: Highways 40-49 (Highway 49) |work = Wisconsin Highways |url = http://www.wisconsinhighways.org/listings/WiscHwys40-49.html#STH-049 |access-date = March 20, 2007 }}{{sps|certain=yes|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n|direction_a=South\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=WI|I|41|US|41|CTH|KK}} in [[Lomira, Wisconsin|Lomira]]\n|junction={{plainlist|1=\n*{{Jct|state=WI|US|151}} in [[Waupun, Wisconsin|Waupun]]\n*{{Jct|state=WI|US|10|WI|110}} in [[Fremont, Wisconsin|Fremont]]\n*{{Jct|state=WI|US|10|WI|54}} in [[Waupaca, Wisconsin|Waupaca]] }}\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=WI|WI|29}} in [[Elderon, Wisconsin|Elderon]]\n|counties=[[Dodge County, Wisconsin|Dodge]], [[Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin|Fond du Lac]], [[Green Lake County, Wisconsin|Green Lake]], [[Waushara County, Wisconsin|Waushara]], [[Waupaca County, Wisconsin|Waupaca]], [[Portage County, Wisconsin|Portage]], [[Marathon County, Wisconsin|Marathon]]\n|previous_type=WI\n|previous_route=48\n|next_type=WI\n|next_route=50\n}}\n'''State Trunk Highway 49''' (often called '''Highway 49''', '''STH-49''' or '''WIS&nbsp;49''') is a [[state highway (US)|state highway]] in the U.S. state of [[Wisconsin]]. It runs north\u2013south in central and southeast Wisconsin from [[Wittenberg, Wisconsin|Wittenberg]] to [[Lomira, Wisconsin|Lomira]]. The highway was initially designated in 1917, but it had not been extended to its current length until the 1950s.\n\n==Route description==\nWIS&nbsp;93 begins at an interchange with [[Interstate 41]] (I-41) north of [[Lomira, Wisconsin|Lomira]] and runs west from it, passing through [[Brownsville, Wisconsin|Brownsville]] before curving to the north to meet the [[Dodge County, Wisconsin|Dodge]]-[[Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin|Fond du Lac]] county line. After an interchange with [[U.S. Route 151|US&nbsp;151]] (US&nbsp;151), WIS&nbsp;49 runs through [[Waupun, Wisconsin|Waupun]]. Shortly after exiting Waupun, the highway curves and starts running north to [[Brandon, Wisconsin|Brandon]]. Shortly after exiting Brandon, the highway [[concurrency (road)|runs concurrently]] with [[Wisconsin Highway 44|WIS&nbsp;44]]. This concurrency ends in [[Ripon, Wisconsin|Ripon]], where a concurrency with [[Wisconsin Highway 23|WIS&nbsp;23]] begins. The highway runs north from the concurrent alignment shortly before it reaches [[Green Lake, Wisconsin|Green Lake]]. While running north, WIS&nbsp;49 runs through [[Berlin, Wisconsin|Berlin]] and many smaller communities before reaching an interchange at [[U.S. Route 10 in Wisconsin|US&nbsp;10]].<ref name=gmaps1/>\n\nThe highway runs concurrently with US 10, which is a [[freeway]] for most of its length. The highway passes by [[Weyauwega, Wisconsin|Weyauwega]] and the [[Waupaca Municipal Airport]] before leaving the concurrency and running through Waupaca. After exiting Waupaca, it runs north to [[Scandinavia, Wisconsin|Scandinavia]] and then to [[Iola, Wisconsin|Iola]], where the highway enters runs concurrently for a short distance with [[Wisconsin Highway 161|WIS&nbsp;161]]. WIS&nbsp;49 then runs northwesterly to [[Wisconsin Highway 66|WIS&nbsp;66]] before continuing north, passing through an intersection with [[Wisconsin Highway 153|WIS&nbsp;153]] in [[Elderon, Wisconsin|Elderon]] before terminating at [[Wisconsin Highway 29|WIS&nbsp;29]].<ref name=gmaps1/><ref name=gmaps2/>\n\n==History==\nWhen Wisconsin's state trunk highways were first designated in 1917, the highway ran from WIS&nbsp;23 near Green Lake to WIS&nbsp;18 (by 1930, this had become US&nbsp;10<ref name=1930map/>) south of Waupaca.<ref>{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |year = 1918 |title = Official Map of the State Trunk Highway System of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/50/rec/57 |scale = [c. 1:1,010,000] |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |id = {{OCLC|69119995|388371736|388371736}} |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 10, 2020 }}</ref> In the early 1920s, WIS&nbsp;49 was extended south to Waupun.<ref name=\"1921map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Conservation Commission |year = c. 1921 |title = Map of the State Highway System of Wisconsin, Showing, Within Red Circle, Location of Northern Lakes Park |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/946/rec/36 |scale = Scale not given |location = n.p. |publisher = Wisconsin State Conservation Commission |oclc = 708376740 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 10, 2020 }}</ref> By 1930, the highway had been extended to its current northern terminus at WIS&nbsp;29, and it was paved south of [[Poy Sippi, Wisconsin|Poy Sippi]] (between WIS&nbsp;21 and US&nbsp;10).<ref name=\"1930map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |year = 1930 |title = Official Highway Map of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/maps/id/14135/rec/43 |scale = 1:823,680 |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |oclc = 429695317 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 10, 2020 }}</ref> In 1933, the section between Poy Sippi and US&nbsp;10 was paved.<ref name=\"1933map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |year = 1933 |title = Official Highway Map of Wisconsin 1933 |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/compoundobject/collection/maps/id/14144/rec/46 |scale = 1:823,680  |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |oclc = 225869984 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 10, 2020 }}</ref> Sometime between 1948 and 1956, the highway had been extended to [[U.S. Route 41 in Wisconsin|US&nbsp;41]] (now I-41/US&nbsp;41<ref name=gmaps1/>). The extension was mostly paved but contained an unpaved section west of Brownsville.<ref name=\"1948map\">{{cite map |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |year = 1948 |title = Preliminary Traffic Map, Showing Annual 24 Hour Average Traffic, State of Wisconsin |url = http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/singleitem/collection/maps/id/14173/rec/69 |scale = [c. 1:1,198,000] |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |oclc = 770711221 |via = Wisconsin Historical Society |access-date = April 10, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"1956maps\">{{cite web |author1 = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |year = 1956 |title = Wisconsin State Atlas 1956 Highway Maps |url = http://www.historicmapworks.com/Atlas/US/9643/Wisconsin+State+Atlas+1956+Highway+Maps/ |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin State Highway Commission |via = Historic Map Works |access-date = April 10, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Major junctions==\n{{Jcttop|exit|exit_ref=<ref name=\"exits\">{{cite book |author = Signs and Markings Implementation Section |date = March 2016 |chapter = Freeway Exit Numbers |chapter-url = https://wisconsindot.gov/dtsdManuals/traffic-ops/manuals-and-standards/teops/02-06.pdf#2-6-19 |title = Traffic Engineering, Operations & Safety Manual |location = Madison |publisher = Wisconsin Department of Transportation |access-date = April 5, 2020 |page = 1  }}</ref>|length_ref=<ref name=\"gmaps1\">{{google maps |title = Length and Route of WIS&nbsp;49 (South of West Main Street) |url = https://www.google.com/maps/dir/43.6162415,-88.4373149/43.6162962,-88.4504619/43.6332693,-88.7150301/43.6332005,-88.724818/43.6330918,-88.7487181/43.7372775,-88.8252827/43.9683457,-88.9442015/44.0427458,-88.9838807/44.3058643,-88.9315901/44.3170518,-88.945026/@43.9336722,-88.9377316,9.13z/am=t/data=!4m27!4m26!1m0!1m0!1m0!1m0!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d-88.7751571!2d43.729831!3s0x880401c3b2273389:0xfb46482cfe9d2609!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d-88.