ad={{jct|state=WI|WI|110|CTH|X|dir1=north}}\n|type=concur\n|notes=Western end of WIS 110 concurrency}}\n{{WIint|exit\n|mile=82.2\n|type=concur\n|location=Waupaca\n|exit=254\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|22|WI|54|CTH|A|CTH|K|dir1=north|dir2=east|dir3=south|dir4=north|city1=Waupaca}}\n|notes=Eastern end of WIS 22/WIS 54 concurrency, access to [[Waupaca Municipal Airport]]}}\n{{WIint|exit\n|town=Waupaca\n|mile=83.8\n|exit=253\n|road=Churchill Street north}}\n{{WIint|exit\n|location=Waupaca\n|mile=85.2\n|exit=252\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WIS|22|dir1=south}}\n|notes=western end of WIS 22 concurrency}}\n{{WIint|exit\n|mile=86.4\n|location1=Farmington\n|location2=Waupaca\n|ctdab1=Waupaca\n|exit=250\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|US|10|WI|54|dir1=west|dir2=west}}\n|notes=Western end of concurrency, freeway section}}\n{{WIint|exit\n|location=Iola\n|lspan=2\n|mile=99.9\n|espan=2\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|161|dir1=east}}\n|notes=Eastern end of concurrency}}\n{{WIint\n|mile=100.5\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|161|dir1=west}}\n|notes=Western end of concurrency}}\n{{WIint|exit\n|county=Portage\n|location=Alban\n|espan=3\n|mile=113.8\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|66|dir1=west}}}}\n{{WIint\n|county=Marathon\n|cspan=2\n|location=Elderon\n|mile=125.1\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|153}}}}\n{{WIint\n|town=elderon\n|mile=128.1\n|road={{jct|state=WI|WI|29}}}}\n{{Jctbtm|exit|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|Wisconsin Highway 49}}\n\n[[Category:State highways in Wisconsin|049]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Dodge County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Green Lake County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Waushara County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Waupaca County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portage County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Marathon County, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Waupaca, Wisconsin]]\n", "name_user": "Imzadi1979", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript; harmonize whitespace in citation templates (usingRegex citation formatter); basic formatting fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wisconsin_Highway_49"}
{"title_page": "Kadawunu Poronduwa", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n | name = Kadawunu Poronduwa\n | image = Kadawunuporonduwa1.jpg\n | imagesize = \n | caption = [[Rukmani Devi]] in a scene\n | director = Jyotish Sinha\n | producer = Chitrakala Movietone Ltd\n | story = B. A. W. Jayamanne\n | screenplay = Roy De Silva, B A. W Jayamanne\n | starring = [[Rukmani Devi]], [[B. A. W. Jayamanne]], Peter Peiris, Miriam Jayamanne, Hugo Fernando, Stanley Mallawarachchi, [[Eddie Jayamanne]], Gemini Kantha, Timothius Perera, J B Perera, Rupa Devi\n | music = Narayana Aiyar\n | cinematography = K Prabhakar\n | editing = Pakeer Saleh\n | distributor = Minerva Group\n | country    = [[Sri Lanka]]\n | released = January 21, 1947 \n | runtime =\n | language = [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]]\n | budget = \n}}\n\n'''''Kadawunu Poronduwa''''' ([[Sinhala language|Sinhala]]: ''\u0d9a\u0da9\u0dc0\u0dd4\u0db1\u0dd4 \u0db4\u0ddc\u0dbb\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dd4\u0dc0'', \"The Broken Promise\") was the first film to be made in the [[Sinhala language]]; it is generally considered to have heralded the coming of Sinhala Cinema. The film was produced and filmed in [[India]] however, and was highly influenced by South Indian melodrama. It was first shown on January 21, 1947 at the Kingsley Cinema in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=dbs>{{Cite web|url=http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/50955|title=First Sinhala Talkie \u201cBroken Promise\u201d was Released 70 Years Ago on Jan 21 1947|authorlink=[[D. B. S. Jeyaraj]]|website=dbsjeyaraj.com|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=20 June 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.is/vKxkt|archivedate=20 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Kadawunu Poronduwa (1982 film)|remake]] was released in 1982.\n\n== Plot ==\n\nRalahamy, a member of high status, dies leaving his family in debt after having squandered his fortune through extensive drinking and other vices. To get back into wealth, Ralahamy's wife Tackla pushes her daughter Ranjani to marry a wealthy older man Victor with a child through an earlier marriage. In this process, Samson, Ranjani's boyfriend, who had tried extensively to get the family back into good graces going so far as to pay off their debts, is spurned. He then goes abroad to win a fortune.\n\nWhen Samson returns he learns of Ranjani's engagement to Victor and tries to reach her through letter. His letters are hidden from her however, and rumours spread that Samson is now a cripple. Ultimately the truth is revealed.\n\n=== Cast ===\n*[[Rukmani Devi]] as Ranjani: A high-class girl who is pushed into a marriage with an older man and forced to reject her boyfriend.\n*[[Gemini Kantha]] as Jossie: village woman; love interest of Manappuwa\n*Rupa Devi as Tackla: Ranjani's mother\n*Miriam Jayamanne as Hilda\n*[[Eddie Jayamanne]] as Manappuwa: naive village simpleton; comic relief\n*[[B. A. W. Jayamanne]] as Samson: Ranjani's love interest; wants financial success for her family but is spurned by the mother\n*Peter Peries as Victor: old wealthy man with whom Ranjani is forcibly engaged\n*Stanley Mallawarachchi as Hemapala\n*D. T. Perera as Jayasena\n*Asilyn Balasooriya as Sumana\n*J. B. Perera as Harmahana\n*[[Hugo Fernando]] as doctor\n*Suriya Rani as Aaya\n*Sina Pishpani as Narsi\n*Wida Soyza\n*S. S. Ponnisena\n\n== Production ==\nKadawunu Poronduwa was produced by [[S. M. Nayagam]],<ref name=dbs /> a pioneer of Sinhala film industry and an Indian citizen. He had to ferry the entire cast to [[Madurai]] India for filming and production. It began as a successful play for dramatist B. A. W. Jayamanne. In 1947 he filmed and processed the movie in South India.<ref name=\"SinhalaFilm\">{{cite book |last=Jayamanne |first=Laleen |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Toward Cinema and Its Double: Cross-cultural Mimesis|year=2001 |publisher=Indiana University Press |location= |isbn= 0-253-21475-0}}</ref>\n\nKadawunu Poronduwa produced a formula that Sinhala films would follow up through the 1960s; Jayamanne describes the formula as such:<ref name=\"SinhalaFilm\"/> {{cquote|The duration of a film had to be two and a half hours. One hour of this had to be given to scenes with dialogue. Half an hour to songs (about ten), another half-hour given to silent background scenes, with an interval of fifteen minutes.}}\n\n==Songs==\n\n*\"Sri Jaya Vijaya\" &ndash; Minerva Singing Group\n*\"Prema Daya\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Lapati Rupe Age\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] (the original gramophone record label was incorrectly printed as \"Eddie jayanamme and Jemini Kantha\")\n*\"Deva Swarmi\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Sandyawe Sriya Ramya Lesa Pena\" &ndash; Rukmani Devi and Hugo Fernando - for film  /  Rukmani Devi and Stanley Mallawarachchi - for gramophone record only\n*\"Is Issara Welaa\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] and Jemini Kantha\n*\"Mage Saka Bambarea\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] and Jemini Kantha\n*\"Thakkita Tharikita\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] and Jemini Kantha\n*\"Jevithaye Saamey\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Yaami Indiya Desataa\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Sundari Rupa Rajini\" &ndash; Stanley Mallawarachchi and Peter Peries\n*\"Papi Shayapi Do\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]] and Hugo Fernando / Stanley Mallawarachchi\n\nSongs of Kadawunu Poronduwa were issued by ''Parlophone'' gramophone records with the film release in 1947. They were the last records issued by the Palophone label in Sri Lanka.\n\nPlease note that the last two songs listed above were not issued on gramophone records and now it is difficult to find them.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Sri Lankan films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.films.lk/FilmDetails.php?id=1/ Sri Lanka Cinema Database]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927044031/http://www.srilankafilmcorp.com/about/ National Film Corporation of Sri Lanka - Official Website]\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan films]]\n[[Category:1940s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in British Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan drama films]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan black-and-white films]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n | name = Kadawunu Poronduwa\n | image = Kadawunuporonduwa1.jpg\n | imagesize = \n | caption = [[Rukmani Devi]] in a scene\n | director = Jyotish Sinha\n | producer = Chitrakala Movietone Ltd\n | story = B. A. W. Jayamanne\n | screenplay = Roy De Silva, B A. W Jayamanne\n | starring = [[Rukmani Devi]], [[B. A. W. Jayamanne]], Peter Peiris, Miriam Jayamanne, Hugo Fernando, Stanley Mallawarachchi, [[Eddie Jayamanne]], Gemini Kantha, Timothius Perera, J B Perera, Rupa Devi\n | music = Narayana Aiyar\n | cinematography = K Prabhakar\n | editing = Pakeer Saleh\n | distributor = Minerva Group\n | country    = [[Sri Lanka]]\n | released = January 21, 1947 \n | runtime =\n | language = [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]]\n | budget = \n}}\n\n'''''Kadawunu Poronduwa''''' ([[Sinhala language|Sinhala]]: ''\u0d9a\u0da9\u0dc0\u0dd4\u0db1\u0dd4 \u0db4\u0ddc\u0dbb\u0ddc\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dd4\u0dc0'', \"The Broken Promise\") was the first film to be made in the [[Sinhala language]]; it is generally considered to have heralded the coming of Sinhala Cinema. The film was produced and filmed in [[India]] however, and was highly influenced by South Indian melodrama. It was first shown on January 21, 1947 at the Kingsley Cinema in [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=dbs>{{Cite web|url=http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/50955|title=First Sinhala Talkie \u201cBroken Promise\u201d was Released 70 Years Ago on Jan 21 1947|authorlink=[[D. B. S. Jeyaraj]]|website=dbsjeyaraj.com|date=26 January 2017|accessdate=20 June 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.is/vKxkt|archivedate=20 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Kadawunu Poronduwa (1982 film)|remake]] was released in 1982.\n\n== Plot ==\n\nRalahamy, a member of high status, dies leaving his family in debt after having squandered his fortune through extensive drinking and other vices. To get back into wealth, Ralahamy's wife Tackla pushes her daughter Ranjani to marry a wealthy older man Victor with a child through an earlier marriage. In this process, Samson, Ranjani's boyfriend, who had tried extensively to get the family back into good graces going so far as to pay off their debts, is spurned. He then goes abroad to win a fortune.\n\nWhen Samson returns he learns of Ranjani's engagement to Victor and tries to reach her through letter. His letters are hidden from her however, and rumours spread that Samson is now a cripple. Ultimately the truth is revealed.\n\n=== Cast ===\n*'''[[Rukmani Devi]]''' as '''Ranjani''': A high-class girl who is pushed into a marriage with an older man and forced to reject her boyfriend.\n*'''[[Gemini Kantha]]''' as '''Jossie''': village woman; love interest of Manappuwa\n*'''Rupa Devi''' as '''Tackla''': Ranjani's mother\n*'''Miriam Jayamanne''' as '''Hilda'''\n*'''[[Eddie Jayamanne]]''' as '''Manappuwa''': naive village simpleton; comic relief\n*'''[[B. A. W. Jayamanne]]''' as '''Samson''': love interest of Ranjani; seeks to help her family achieve financial success but is spurned by the mother\n*'''Peter Peries''' as '''Victor''': old wealthy man with whom Ranjani is forcibly engaged\n*'''Stanley Mallawarachchi''' as '''Hemapala'''\n*'''D. T. Perera''' as '''Jayasena'''\n*'''Asilyn Balasooriya''' as '''Sumana'''\n*'''J. B. Perera''' as '''Harmahana'''\n*'''[[Hugo Fernando]]''' as '''doctor'''\n*'''Suriya Rani''' as '''Aaya'''\n*'''Sina Pishpani''' as '''Narsi'''\n*'''Wida Soyza'''\n*'''S. S. Ponnisena'''\n\n== Production ==\nKadawunu Poronduwa was produced by [[S. M. Nayagam]],<ref name=dbs /> a pioneer of Sinhala film industry and an Indian citizen. He had to ferry the entire cast to [[Madurai]] India for filming and production. It began as a successful play for dramatist B. A. W. Jayamanne. In 1947 he filmed and processed the movie in South India.<ref name=\"SinhalaFilm\">{{cite book |last=Jayamanne |first=Laleen |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Toward Cinema and Its Double: Cross-cultural Mimesis|year=2001 |publisher=Indiana University Press |location= |isbn= 0-253-21475-0}}</ref>\n\nKadawunu Poronduwa produced a formula that Sinhala films would follow up through the 1960s; Jayamanne describes the formula as such:<ref name=\"SinhalaFilm\"/> {{cquote|The duration of a film had to be two and a half hours. One hour of this had to be given to scenes with dialogue. Half an hour to songs (about ten), another half-hour given to silent background scenes, with an interval of fifteen minutes.}}\n\n==Songs==\n\n*\"Sri Jaya Vijaya\" &ndash; Minerva Singing Group\n*\"Prema Daya\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Lapati Rupe Age\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] (the original gramophone record label was incorrectly printed as \"Eddie jayanamme and Jemini Kantha\")\n*\"Deva Swarmi\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Sandyawe Sriya Ramya Lesa Pena\" &ndash; Rukmani Devi and Hugo Fernando - for film  /  Rukmani Devi and Stanley Mallawarachchi - for gramophone record only\n*\"Is Issara Welaa\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] and Jemini Kantha\n*\"Mage Saka Bambarea\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] and Jemini Kantha\n*\"Thakkita Tharikita\" &ndash; [[Eddie Jayamanne]] and Jemini Kantha\n*\"Jevithaye Saamey\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Yaami Indiya Desataa\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]]\n*\"Sundari Rupa Rajini\" &ndash; Stanley Mallawarachchi and Peter Peries\n*\"Papi Shayapi Do\" &ndash; [[Rukmani Devi]] and Hugo Fernando / Stanley Mallawarachchi\n\nSongs of Kadawunu Poronduwa were issued by ''Parlophone'' gramophone records with the film release in 1947. They were the last records issued by the Palophone label in Sri Lanka.\n\nPlease note that the last two songs listed above were not issued on gramophone records and now it is difficult to find them.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Sri Lankan films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.films.lk/FilmDetails.php?id=1/ Sri Lanka Cinema 